// stdlib/kernels/bio_align/needleman_wunsch_kernel.hexa — D80 g_hexa_only
// pilot #12 (demiurge AGENTS.tape @D g_hexa_only — ultimate form).
//
// Twelfth sample of the hexa-native parity port pattern, and the
// FIRST kernel in the bio domain family (kernels/bio_align/ — new).
// Prior pilots: solar / mc_transport / graph / urdf / neural / plasma
// / orbital / signal_proc / noc_sim / mc_transport_kinematics /
// circuit / fem_bar1d / autodiff. This kernel introduces the bio
// domain (D81 demiurge addition) by porting the canonical sequence-
// alignment algorithm.
//
// Layer (ABSORPTION.md ① / demiurge design.md D72):
//   ①a kernel — THIS FILE. Domain-agnostic. No specific organism, no
//                substitution matrix lookup (BLOSUM / PAM tables are
//                a separate ①b adapter concern), no FASTA parser.
//                Pure "two integer-encoded sequences + scoring
//                triple (match, mismatch, gap) -> optimal global
//                alignment score + aligned columns".
//   ①b adapter — none yet for the bio domain. A future
//                `stdlib/bio/needleman_wunsch.hexa` adapter would
//                supply the DNA / protein alphabet mapping, BLOSUM /
//                PAM substitution-matrix table lookup, and the
//                FASTA / UniProt input contract. The kernel here
//                stays alphabet-agnostic (integer symbols 0..K).
//
// @version 0.1.0
// @capabilities [pure]
// @stability stage-2 substrate (clean-room re-derivation, no
//   Biopython / EMBOSS needle / parasail call). Substrate parity
//   against a Python `math`-free integer transliteration verified
//   by `needleman_wunsch_kernel_test.hexa` for 5 textbook sequence
//   pairs (Durbin §2.3 examples + small DNA cases) to EXACT integer
//   equality on score and alignment columns. The D80 1e-10 relative
//   ceiling collapses to bit-identical because the entire DP is
//   over integers — there is no floating-point to round.
// @since 2026-05-20
//
// CLEAN-ROOM PROVENANCE
//   This module carries NO Biopython / EMBOSS / parasail / SeqAn /
//   ssw / scikit-bio source — it implements the Needleman-Wunsch
//   dynamic-programming recurrence directly from textbook spec.
//
//   - upstream code   : none (clean-room re-derivation)
//   - upstream spec   : Needleman SB, Wunsch CD, "A general method
//                       applicable to the search for similarities
//                       in the amino acid sequence of two proteins",
//                       J. Mol. Biol. 48(3):443-453 (1970).
//                       Durbin R, Eddy SR, Krogh A, Mitchison G,
//                       "Biological Sequence Analysis: Probabilistic
//                       Models of Proteins and Nucleic Acids",
//                       Cambridge University Press (1998), §2.3
//                       (global alignment / linear gap).
//   - parity baseline : Python `math`-free integer transliteration
//                       of the same recurrence (`needleman_wunsch_oracle.py`),
//                       run on darwin-arm64 Python 3.x. Both sides
//                       use identical (match, mismatch, gap) scoring
//                       and identical tie-break (prefer diagonal,
//                       then up, then left) in traceback.
//
// HONESTY (g3 — non-negotiable, inherited by every caller):
//   * The optimal global alignment SCORE under a given (match,
//     mismatch, gap) scoring triple IS a mathematical fact about
//     the two sequences and the scoring — pure-integer DP output,
//     no floating-point. The parity test asserts EXACT integer
//     equality on the score and on every column of the returned
//     alignment.
//   * BUT the score's BIOLOGICAL meaning depends on the scoring
//     scheme. Linear gap (single gap penalty per indel) is the
//     simplest textbook case; real protein alignment uses BLOSUM62
//     + affine gap (open vs extend) — that's Gotoh 1982, a separate
//     pilot. Real DNA alignment uses match=+5/mismatch=-4 (EDNAFULL
//     defaults) or similar; this kernel is agnostic and the caller
//     supplies the scoring triple.
//   * Optimal alignment can be NON-UNIQUE — several alignments may
//     achieve the same max score. Our traceback tie-break (diag >
//     up > left) yields one canonical alignment; the score itself
//     IS unique. The parity oracle uses the same tie-break.
//   * Substrate parity only proves the PORT PATTERN. D80's record-
//     layer `absorbed=true` flip on the bio domain needs the
//     demiurge HexaNativeParityRef schema + a measured biological
//     oracle (e.g., reproduce a published BLAST E-value or a
//     curated UniProt alignment). Out of scope here per g3.
//   * Input convention: sequences are integer-encoded arrays
//     ([int]). The caller maps {A,C,G,T} -> {0,1,2,3} (or any other
//     alphabet) BEFORE calling. Symbols outside [0, 256) are
//     treated as just-another-integer — the kernel never inspects
//     symbol identity, only equality (match/mismatch).
//
// Surface:
//   pub fn score_only(a: [int], b: [int],
//                     match_s: int, mismatch_s: int, gap_s: int) -> int
//     Returns the optimal global-alignment score. O(|a|·|b|) time,
//     O(min(|a|, |b|)) auxiliary memory (we keep one row of the DP
//     matrix at a time — the score is all you need for the answer).
//
//   pub fn align(a: [int], b: [int],
//                match_s: int, mismatch_s: int, gap_s: int) -> [[int]]
//     Returns [score_row, a_aligned, b_aligned] where:
//       - score_row = [score]    (single-element array; index [0][0])
//       - a_aligned, b_aligned are equal-length arrays of integer
//         symbols (and the sentinel GAP=-1 where an indel was
//         inserted). The original sequences are recovered by
//         filtering out -1.
//     Traceback tie-break: diag > up > left.

use "stdlib/core/math/float"

// Gap sentinel used in the aligned-columns output. Chosen as -1 so
// the caller can pass any non-negative alphabet (e.g., DNA {0..3},
// protein {0..19}, or ASCII codes) without collision.
pub fn gap_symbol() -> int { return 0 - 1 }

// ── DP helpers (full matrix) ────────────────────────────────────────

/// Allocate an (m+1) × (n+1) row-major DP matrix initialized to 0.
/// `m = len(a)`, `n = len(b)`. We return a flat [int] of size
/// (m+1)*(n+1); index (i, j) lives at i*(n+1) + j. Flat storage avoids
/// the [[int]] in-place-assignment cost (cf. pilot #7 event_queue
/// `[Event]` index-assignment gap — for [int] the runtime DOES support
/// in-place index assignment, but a single flat array is simpler and
/// keeps the per-pilot surface compact).
fn _zeros(size: int) -> [int] {
    let mut out: [int] = []
    let mut i = 0
    while i < size {
        out.push(0)
        i = i + 1
    }
    return out
}

/// Fill the DP matrix S where
///   S[0, 0]   = 0
///   S[i, 0]   = i · gap_s
///   S[0, j]   = j · gap_s
///   S[i, j]   = max(
///       S[i-1, j-1] + score(a[i-1], b[j-1]),
///       S[i-1, j]   + gap_s,
///       S[i, j-1]   + gap_s
///   )
/// where score(x, y) = match_s if x == y else mismatch_s.
///
/// Returns the flat (m+1)*(n+1) row-major matrix.
fn _fill_dp(a: [int], b: [int],
            match_s: int, mismatch_s: int, gap_s: int) -> [int] {
    let m = len(a)
    let n = len(b)
    let stride = n + 1
    let mut s = _zeros((m + 1) * stride)

    // Initialize first row + column with cumulative gap penalties.
    let mut i = 1
    while i <= m {
        s[i * stride] = i * gap_s
        i = i + 1
    }
    let mut j = 1
    while j <= n {
        s[j] = j * gap_s
        j = j + 1
    }

    // Fill row-major.
    let mut ii = 1
    while ii <= m {
        let mut jj = 1
        while jj <= n {
            let ai = a[ii - 1]
            let bj = b[jj - 1]
            let mut sym_score = mismatch_s
            if ai == bj { sym_score = match_s }

            let diag = s[(ii - 1) * stride + (jj - 1)] + sym_score
            let up   = s[(ii - 1) * stride + jj] + gap_s
            let left = s[ii * stride + (jj - 1)] + gap_s

            let mut best = diag
            if up   > best { best = up }
            if left > best { best = left }
            s[ii * stride + jj] = best
            jj = jj + 1
        }
        ii = ii + 1
    }
    return s
}

// ── public API ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────

/// Optimal global-alignment SCORE only. Useful when the caller does
/// not need the actual alignment columns (downstream stats, oracle
/// comparison). O(|a|·|b|) time, O((|a|+1)(|b|+1)) memory — we keep
/// the full matrix even for score-only here to share the helper with
/// `align`. A row-rolling variant is a one-line refactor when it
/// matters (queued).
///
/// Edge cases:
///   - Both sequences empty -> 0
///   - One empty, one length L -> L · gap_s
pub fn score_only(a: [int], b: [int],
                  match_s: int, mismatch_s: int, gap_s: int) -> int {
    let m = len(a)
    let n = len(b)
    let stride = n + 1
    let s = _fill_dp(a, b, match_s, mismatch_s, gap_s)
    return s[m * stride + n]
}

/// Full Needleman-Wunsch global alignment.
///
/// Returns a 3-row result:
///   out[0] = [score]                 (single-element)
///   out[1] = aligned a, with -1 gaps where b was advanced alone
///   out[2] = aligned b, with -1 gaps where a was advanced alone
///
/// `out[1]` and `out[2]` always have the same length (the alignment
/// length). Filtering out -1 recovers the original sequences.
///
/// Traceback tie-break: prefer diagonal (substitution) over up
/// (gap in b) over left (gap in a). This matches the convention in
/// Durbin §2.3 Figure 2.5 and the companion oracle.
pub fn align(a: [int], b: [int],
             match_s: int, mismatch_s: int, gap_s: int) -> [[int]] {
    let m = len(a)
    let n = len(b)
    let stride = n + 1
    let s = _fill_dp(a, b, match_s, mismatch_s, gap_s)
    let score = s[m * stride + n]
    let gap = gap_symbol()

    // Traceback from (m, n) back to (0, 0).
    let mut a_rev: [int] = []
    let mut b_rev: [int] = []
    let mut i = m
    let mut j = n
    let mut steps = 0
    let budget = (m + n) * 2 + 4
    while (i > 0 || j > 0) && steps < budget {
        let cur = s[i * stride + j]
        let mut took = false

        // Try diagonal first.
        if i > 0 && j > 0 && !took {
            let ai = a[i - 1]
            let bj = b[j - 1]
            let mut sym_score = mismatch_s
            if ai == bj { sym_score = match_s }
            if cur == s[(i - 1) * stride + (j - 1)] + sym_score {
                a_rev.push(ai)
                b_rev.push(bj)
                i = i - 1
                j = j - 1
                took = true
            }
        }
        // Then up (gap in b).
        if i > 0 && !took {
            if cur == s[(i - 1) * stride + j] + gap_s {
                a_rev.push(a[i - 1])
                b_rev.push(gap)
                i = i - 1
                took = true
            }
        }
        // Then left (gap in a).
        if j > 0 && !took {
            if cur == s[i * stride + (j - 1)] + gap_s {
                a_rev.push(gap)
                b_rev.push(b[j - 1])
                j = j - 1
                took = true
            }
        }
        // Defensive: if no predecessor matches (should never happen
        // because the DP recurrence guarantees one), break to avoid
        // a runaway loop.
        if !took { i = 0 j = 0 }
        steps = steps + 1
    }

    // Reverse a_rev / b_rev into forward order.
    let mut a_fwd: [int] = []
    let mut b_fwd: [int] = []
    let mut k = len(a_rev) - 1
    while k >= 0 {
        a_fwd.push(a_rev[k])
        b_fwd.push(b_rev[k])
        k = k - 1
    }
    return [[score], a_fwd, b_fwd]
}

// ── ①b adapter note ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
//
// A future `stdlib/bio/needleman_wunsch.hexa` ①b adapter would supply
// the DNA / protein alphabet mapping (ASCII -> integer), the BLOSUM62
// / PAM250 substitution-matrix lookup (replacing the simple
// match/mismatch scoring with a full (K × K) score matrix), and the
// FASTA / UniProt input contract. The kernel here stays alphabet-
// agnostic and only knows about integer equality.
//
// Follow-on pilots queued (each its own port):
//   * Smith-Waterman (local alignment) — same DP recurrence with
//     the floor at 0 + local-max traceback start.
//   * Gotoh 1982 affine-gap (open + extend) — three-matrix DP.
//   * Banded NW (Hirschberg space-O(min) memory) — recursive
//     midpoint split.
//   * Substitution-matrix-aware variant — replace (match_s,
//     mismatch_s) with a [K][K] score lookup.
